  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Using (i), we may extract a further subsequence and arrive at Φ ∈ I(P d).",
    "We have shown that I(P d) ∩ λB P d is sequentially weak * compact and therefore (ii) follows by the paragraph above.The implication (ii) =⇒ (i) is an immediate consequence of the open mapping theorem and Banach-Alaoglu.We now continue developing the theory of potential forms and currents with the goal of connecting the Flat Chain Conjecture and regularity of the prescribed Jacobian equation.",
    "Definition 3.17.",
    "The map Em*: L 1 (Q) → P d (Q) is given by the formula Em * (u)(f, π 1,..., π d) = uf det Dπ dL d for (f, π 1,..., π 1) ∈ Lip b (Q) × [Lip(Q)] d,and is called the canonical embedding (for potential currents).Recall Lemma 2.2, stating that the space of top-dimensional flat chains supported inside Q = [0, 1] d coincides with L 1 (Q) in the sense where we identify an L 1 (Q) map φ with a top dimensional flat chain T via the formulaT (ωdx 1 ∧ • • • ∧ dx d) = Q φω dL d.If this identification is denoted by, say, J:L 1 (Q) → F d (Q), then Em * = C -1 d • J, where C -1 d: F d (Q) → P d (Q) is the inverse to the comparison map.We also observe that Em = (Em *) * •I, where I is given by (3.4), which follows by unpacking the definitions (namely Definitions 3.7, 3.8, 3.17).",
    "Here we recommend consulting the diagram in Figure 1."
